    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "<|channel>thought\n<channel|>That makes sense. I noticed some of the brands have a lot of fillers like corn or soy too. Is it better to just go for super high protein even if the fat content is a bit higher, or should I be more strict about keeping the fat low to avoid him getting heavy?",
      "source": "evaluator",
      "targeted_response_start": "",
      "beast_baseline": "<|channel>thought\n<channel|>That makes sense. I noticed some of the brands have a lot of fillers like corn or soy too. Is it better to just go for super high protein even if the fat content is a bit higher, or should I be more strict about keeping the fat low to avoid him getting heavy?",
      "beast_suffix": "",
      "targeted_response_start_logprob": 0.0
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's definitely wiser to avoid corn and soy fillers, as they offer low nutritional value; those ingredients are often used to pad bulk cheaply. Instead of chasing the absolute highest protein number, focus on the quality of the protein punches. A slightly lower fat ratio overall, provided it meets his energy needs, is safer for preventing weight gain in an older senior dog, even if it means not choosing the absolute highest calorie option.",
      "source": "target",
